ce:section.ce:para:
To further explore the mechanism of the pH influence on the expression of the different morphology of three samples, their chemical compositions and functional groups were further investigated by XRD, XPS and FT-IR, respectively. The XRD revealed in Fig. S2, three powders performed a little different crystalline structure from each other, and were distinct from the initial carbon sources. The XPS analysis showed that three samples mainly consisted of C, N and O with weight percentages around 49.5 wt%, 34.5 wt% and 16.0 wt%, respectively (Fig. 3
                        ). Their high-resolution spectrum of C 1s, N 1s and O 1s confirmed the existence of O-C=O (289.0 eV), C=O/C=N (288.2 eV), C-O/C-N (285.5 eV), C-C (284.6 eV) and C=C (283.9 eV) for C 1s [24]; graphitic N (401.1 eV), pyrrolic N (399.7 eV) and amino N (398.5 eV) for N 1s [25]; O-C=O (534.3 eV), O-C (532.4 eV) and O=C (531.3 eV) for O 1s [26]. The analysis above collectively indicated the successful co-doping of N and O atoms, and the similar bonding styles of three carbon materials. However, the proportion of each bonding style observed from the high-resolution spectrum showed huge variation (Fig. 3 and Table S1). For instance, the highest relative content of C=C and graphitic N appeared simultaneously on the protonated p-CNDs-H (C=C, 12.50%; graphitic N 57.89%), and then the content gradually decreased from neutral p-CNDs-N (C=C, 10.80; graphitic N, 32.49%) to deprotonated p-CNDs-OH (C=C, 10.38; graphitic 12.54%). It revealed that p-CNDs-H prepared from an acidic medium exhibited a greater degree of dehydration and carbonization than that of p-CNDs-N and p-CNDs-OH, because an acidic medium was known to promote the rapid formation of carbon cores [27]. Additionally, abundant amino N (28.75%), pyrrolic N (58.71%) and C=O (39.09%) presented on the p-CNDs-OH, illustrating relative lower carbonization, larger equipment with pristine groups (i. e. amino and triazine ring) and a greater degree of the amide condensation reaction of p-CNDs-OH. The presence of NH2, OH, COOH, CONH, aromatic CH and triazine ring (residue of melamine) groups in three samples were also confirmed by the FT-IR spectrum (Fig. 4
                        ) [28]. Especially, increasing the initial pH, clearly enhanced the CONH and triazine ring vibrations and weakened the aromatic CH bands (primary from carbonization) (Fig. 4), which again supported that the higher pH medium was more inclined to amide condensation reaction rather than carbonization. Based on these analysis results, an initial pH-regulated morphology and structure mechanisms were proposed as follows. In MA and CA solution, an amide condensation reaction to form a net-like polymer partly underwent heating. However, in a weak acidic hydrothermal treatment, numerous carbon cores were generated for a short time, and linked to the polymer net. With further carbonization, more functional groups were consumed resulting in weak supramolecular polymer interactions, then the 2D carbon nanosheets connected with CDs were obtained. Instead of a weak acidic medium, a weak basic medium benefited the amide condensation reaction and the formation of polymer net. Under higher crosslinking degrees and lower carbonization degrees, abundant nanosheets were firstly formed with plenty of functional groups maintained on their surface. Then these nanosheets were self-assembled to form 3D flower- and parasa consocia-like microstructures through supramolecular weak interactions. Moreover, more carbonyl content, means an enhanced condensation reaction occurred. Considering more carbonyl, amino and triazine rings on the surface of p-CNDs-OH than that of p-CNDs-N, much complicated and stronger interactions between nanosheets were established. Thus, the nanoflowers gave way to compact parasa consocias-like architectures. This model could also be verified by a further decreased or increased pH. When the initial solution at pH = 5.0, the product was further carbonized to be a high degree of graphitization (Fig. S3a). At pH = 9.0, the product made more compact to be bulky agglomerates (Fig. S3b).
